 client herself is not aware about the exact need but is ready to make a change?<\/span><\/p><p><span style=\"color: var( --e-global-color-text ); font-family: var( --e-global-typography-text-font-family ), Sans-serif; font-size: var( --e-global-typography-text-font-size ); font-weight: var( --e-global-typography-text-font-weight );\">Most of the sales professionals believe that their customer would be clear about the need. Is that always true?<\/span><\/p><p><span style=\"color: var( --e-global-color-text ); font-family: var( --e-global-typography-text-font-family ), Sans-serif; font-size: var( --e-global-typography-text-font-size ); font-weight: var( --e-global-typography-text-font-weight );\">Perhaps such instances (of client unsure about her need) are relatively less.<\/span><\/p><p>I thought so initially. However lately I am realising that this % is much higher than I initially thought.<\/p><p><span style=\"color: var( --e-global-color-text ); font-family: var( --e-global-typography-text-font-family ), Sans-serif; font-size: var( --e-global-typography-text-font-size ); font-weight: var( --e-global-typography-text-font-weight );\">We were also taught that B2B Sales guys should be good listeners, should be good in asking insightful questions. I am in sync with these learnings.<\/span><\/p><p><span style=\"color: var( --e-global-color-text ); font-family: var( --e-global-typography-text-font-family ), Sans-serif; font-size: var( --e-global-typography-text-font-size ); font-weight: var( --e-global-typography-text-font-weight );\">However, are these teachings applicable in case of \u201ccustomer unaware about her need\u201d?\u00a0<\/span><\/p>\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<section class=\"elementor-section elementor-inner-section elementor-element elementor-element-217d3d9 elementor-section-full_width elementor-section-height-default elementor-section-height-default\" data-id=\"217d3d9\" data-element_type=\"section\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"el